<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-deriv-mcq-1">
  <title>Laplace Transform of a First Derivative</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the Laplace transform of <m>y'(t)</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>sY(s) - y(0)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. <m>{\cal L}\{y'\} = sY(s) - y(0)</m>, which is crucial when solving ODEs with initial conditions.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>sY(s)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Missing the important term <m>-y(0)</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>Y(s) - y(0)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect scaling—the factor <m>s</m> is essential.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-deriv-mcq-2">
  <title>Laplace Transform of a Second Derivative</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      What is <m>{\cal L}\{y''(t)\}</m> in terms of <m>Y(s)</m>, <m>y(0)</m>, and <m>y'(0)</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>s^{2}Y(s) - s\,y(0) - y'(0)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. <m>{\cal L}\{y''\} = s^2Y(s) - s y(0) - y'(0)</m>, used directly when turning ODEs into algebraic equations in <m>s</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>s^{2}Y(s) - y(0)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Missing the critical <m>-s y(0)</m> and <m>-y'(0)</m> terms.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>sY(s) - y'(0)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>This is the formula for <em>first</em> derivatives, not second.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-deriv-mcq-3">
  <title>Converting an ODE to an Algebraic Equation</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the IVP <m>y'' + y = 0</m> with <m>y(0)=2</m>, <m>y'(0)=0</m>.  
      After taking Laplace transforms and using derivative rules, which algebraic equation in <m>Y(s)</m> results?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>(s^{2}+1)Y(s) - 2s = 0</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Using <m>{\cal L}\{y''\}=s^2Y - s y(0) - y'(0) = s^2Y -2s</m> and <m>{\cal L}\{y\}=Y</m>.  
          So <m>(s^2+1)Y - 2s = 0</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>(s^{2}+1)Y(s)=0</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Initial conditions were not incorporated.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>(s^{2}-1)Y(s)=2</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect signs and missing <m>s</m>-term.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-deriv-mcq-4">
  <title>Solve for <m>Y(s)</m></title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      From the algebraic equation <m>(s^{2}+1)Y(s) - 2s = 0</m>, what is <m>Y(s)</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>Y(s) = \dfrac{2s}{s^{2}+1}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Divide both sides by <m>s^{2}+1</m>.  
          This corresponds to the transform of <m>2\cos t</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>Y(s)=\dfrac{2}{s^{2}+1}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Missing a factor of <m>s</m> in the numerator.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>Y(s)=\dfrac{2s}{s^{2}-1}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect denominator.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-deriv-mcq-5">
  <title>Inverse Laplace Identification</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Which of the following time‑domain functions have Laplace transforms equal to 
      <m>\dfrac{2s}{s^{2}+1}</m>?  
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>2\cos t</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Since <m>{\cal L}\{\cos t\} = s/(s^{2}+1)</m>, multiplying by 2 gives the target transform.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>2\sin t</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—its transform is <m>2/(s^{2}+1)</m>, not <m>2s/(s^{2}+1)</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>e^{-t}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—its transform is <m>1/(s+1)</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-next-line-table321">
  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the next line in 
      <url href="https://web.uvic.ca/~tbazett/diffyqs/transformsofders_section.html#ltd_table">
        Table 3.2.1
      </url>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Table 3.2.1 lists transforms of derivatives.  
      After the line
    </p>
    <me>
      {\cal L}\{y'''(t)\} = s^3G(s) - s^2g(0)-sg'(0)-g''(0),
    </me>
    <p>
      the next line is the transform of the second derivative:
    </p>
    <me>
      {\cal L}\{y''''(t)\} = s^{4}G(s) - s^3g(0) - s^2g'(0)-sg''(0)-g'''(0).
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-plot-step-shifted">
  <statement>
    <p>Plot the following functions.</p>

    <ol marker="(a)">
      <li><p><m>f(t) = u(t-\pi)\sin t</m></p></li>
      <li><p><m>u(t-1) - u(t-2)</m></p></li>
      <li><p><m>t(u(t)-u(t-1)) + (-t+2)(u(t-1)-u(t-2))</m></p></li>
    </ol>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      <strong>(a)</strong>  
      <m>u(t-\pi)\sin t</m> is <m>0</m> for <m>t &lt; \pi</m> and equals <m>\sin t</m> for <m>t\ge \pi</m>.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>Graph of <m>u(t-\pi)\sin t</m></caption>
      <image width="60%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \begin{axis}[xmin=0,xmax=8,ymin=-1.5,ymax=1.5,axis lines=middle]
              \addplot[domain=0:3.14,thick] {0};
              \addplot[domain=3.14:8,samples=200,very thick, blue] {sin(deg(x))};
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      <strong>(b)</strong>  
      <m>u(t-1)-u(t-2)</m> equals <m>1</m> on <m>[1,2)</m> and <m>0</m> elsewhere.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <caption>Graph of <m>u(t-1)-u(t-2)</m></caption>
      <image width="60%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \begin{axis}[xmin=0,xmax=4,ymin=0,ymax=1.5,axis lines=middle]
              \addplot[domain=0:1,thick] {0};
              \addplot[domain=1:2,very thick, blue] {1};
              \addplot[domain=2:4,thick] {0};
            \end{axis}
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      <strong>(c)</strong>  
      This describes a “piecewise linear bump” between <m>0</m> and <m>2</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      f(t)=
      \begin{cases}
        t, \amp 0\le t &lt; 1,\\
        -t+2, \amp 1\le t &lt; 2,\\
        0, \amp t\ge 2.
      \end{cases}
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-ivp-sin3t">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Using the Laplace transform, solve the IVP
    </p>
    <me>
      y'' + 4y = \sin 3t, \quad y(0)=0,\; y'(0)=0.
    </me>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Laplace transforming:
    </p>
    <me>
      s^{2}Y(s) + 4Y(s) = \frac{3}{s^{2}+9}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Solve for <m>Y(s)</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      Y(s) = \frac{3}{(s^{2}+4)(s^{2}+9)}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Use partial fractions:
    </p>
    <me>
      \frac{3}{(s^{2}+4)(s^{2}+9)}
      = \frac{3}{5}\frac{1}{s^{2}+4}
        - \frac{3}{5}\frac{1}{s^{2}+9}.
    </me>

    <p>Invert term‑by‑term:</p>
    <md>
      <mrow> y(t)
      \amp = \frac{3}{5}\cdot \frac12\sin 2t
        - \frac{3}{5}\cdot \frac13\sin 3t </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \frac{3}{10}\sin 2t - \frac{1}{5}\sin 3t. </mrow>
    </md>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-ivp-homogeneous">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Solve the IVP
    </p>
    <me>
      y'' - y' - 6y = 0, \qquad y(0) = 2, \; y'(0) = -1.
    </me>
    <p>
      using the Laplace transform.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Take Laplace transforms term-by-term:
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}\{y''\} = s^{2}Y(s) - s y(0) - y'(0)
      = s^{2}Y - 2s + 1,
    </me>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}\{y'\} = sY - y(0) = sY - 2,
    </me>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}\{y\} = Y.
    </me>

    <p>
      Substitute into <m>y'' - y' - 6y = 0</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      (s^{2}Y - 2s + 1) - (sY - 2) - 6Y = 0.
    </me>

    <p>
      Combine like terms:
    </p>

    <me>
      (s^{2} - s - 6)Y - 2s + 3 = 0.
    </me>

    <p>
      Solve for <m>Y(s)</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      Y(s) = \frac{2s - 3}{(s - 3)(s + 2)}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Use partial fractions:
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{2s - 3}{(s - 3)(s + 2)}
      = \frac{3/5}{s - 3} + \frac{7/5}{s + 2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Invert term-by-term:
    </p>

    <me>
      y(t)
      = \frac{3}{5} e^{3t} + \frac{7}{5} e^{-2t}.
    </me>

    <p>
      This satisfies the differential equation and initial conditions, so it is the correct solution.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-shifting-theorem">
  <statement>
    <p>
      (Shifting Theorem)  
      Suppose <m>{\cal L}[f(t)] = F(s)</m> for <m>s>c</m>.  
      Show that for any real <m>a</m> and <m>s>a+c</m>,
    </p>
    <me>
      {\cal L}[e^{at} f(t)](s) = F(s-a).
    </me>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      This follows directly because
    </p>
    <md>
      <mrow> {\cal L}[e^{at}f(t)](s)
      \amp = \int_0^\infty e^{-st} e^{at}f(t)\,dt </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = \int_0^\infty e^{-(s-a)t}f(t)\,dt </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = F(s-a). </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>
      The domain shifts by replacing <m>s</m> with <m>s-a</m>, requiring <m>s-a>c</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-inverse-shifted-t2">
  <statement>
    <p>
      We know that 
      <m>{\cal L}[t^{2}](s) = \frac{2}{s^{3}}</m>.  
      Compute 
      <m>{\cal L}^{-1}\!\left[\frac{2}{(s-2)^{3}}\right]</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      We start from the known transform
    </p>
    <me>
      {\cal L}[t^{2}](s) = \frac{2}{s^{3}}.
    </me>

    <p>
      The expression 
      <m>\dfrac{2}{(s-2)^{3}}</m>
      is obtained by replacing <m>s</m> with <m>s-2</m> in 
      <m>\dfrac{2}{s^{3}}</m>.  
      By the (exponential) shifting theorem,
    </p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}[e^{at}f(t)] = F(s-a).
    </me>

    <p>
      Here, <m>F(s) = \dfrac{2}{s^{3}}</m> corresponds to <m>f(t)=t^{2}</m>,  
      and we need <m>F(s-2)</m>.  
      Therefore
    </p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}^{-1}\!\left[\frac{2}{(s-2)^{3}}\right]
      = e^{2t} \, t^{2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus the inverse Laplace transform is
    </p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}^{-1}\!\left[\frac{2}{(s-2)^{3}}\right]
      = t^{2} e^{2t}.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-piecewise-f-transform-2">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Define
    </p>
    <me>
      f(t) =
      \left\{
      \begin{array}{cr}
        1 \amp 0 \le t &lt; 1 \\
        3 \amp 1 \le t &lt; 2 \\
        t \amp 2 \le t &lt; \infty
      \end{array}
      \right\}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Compute the Laplace transform <m>{\cal L}[f(t)]</m>.  
      <em>Hint:</em> Write
    </p>

    <me>
      f(t)
      =
      \bigl[1 - 1\cdot u(t-1)\bigr]
      +
      \bigl[3u(t-1) - 3u(t-2)\bigr]
      +
      \bigl[t\,u(t-2)\bigr].
    </me>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Using the decomposition:
    </p>

    <ol marker="(1)">
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>First term:</strong>
        </p>
        <me>
          {\cal L}[\,1 - u(t-1)\,](s)
          = \frac{1}{s} - \frac{e^{-s}}{s}.
        </me>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Second term:</strong>
        </p>
        <me>
          {\cal L}[\,3u(t-1) - 3u(t-2)\,](s)
          = \frac{3e^{-s}}{s} - \frac{3e^{-2s}}{s}.
        </me>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Third term:</strong>
          We use the shifting rule
          <m>{\cal L}[\,t\,u(t-a)\,] = e^{-as}\Bigl(\frac{1}{s^{2}} + \frac{a}{s}\Bigr)</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Here <m>a=2</m>, so
        </p>

        <me>
          {\cal L}[\,t\,u(t-2)\,](s)
          = e^{-2s}\!\left(\frac{1}{s^{2}} + \frac{2}{s}\right).
        </me>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      Now sum all terms:
    </p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}[f(t)](s)
      =
      \left(\frac{1}{s} - \frac{e^{-s}}{s}\right)
      +
      \left(\frac{3e^{-s}}{s} - \frac{3e^{-2s}}{s}\right)
      +
      e^{-2s}\!\left(\frac{1}{s^{2}} + \frac{2}{s}\right).
    </me>

    <p>
      Combine like terms:
    </p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}[f(t)]
      =
      \frac{1}{s}
      +
      \frac{2e^{-s}}{s}
      +
      e^{-2s}\!\left(
        \frac{1}{s^{2}}
        + \frac{2}{s}
        - \frac{3}{s}
      \right).
    </me>

    <p>
      Simplify the expression inside the final brackets:
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{1}{s^{2}} + \frac{2}{s} - \frac{3}{s}
      = \frac{1}{s^{2}} - \frac{1}{s}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus the Laplace transform is
    </p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}[f(t)](s)
      = \frac{1}{s}
        + \frac{2e^{-s}}{s}
        + e^{-2s}\!\left(\frac{1}{s^{2}} - \frac{1}{s}\right).
    </me>

  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-mass-spring-piecwise-force">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A mass that weighs 32 lb (<m>m=1</m> slug) is attached to a spring that is stretched 
      1 ft by a force of 4 lb (<m>k=4</m> lb/ft).  
      The mass is initially at rest in equilibrium.  
      A forcing function <m>f(t)=1</m> is applied for <m>0 \le t &lt; \pi</m> and then turned off for <m>t\ge \pi</m>.  
      (Assume no damping.)  
      Find the resulting position <m>x(t)</m>.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="SpringMass4b" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <caption>A dashpot (not active here, since <m>c=0</m>).</caption>
      <image source="SpringMass4.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>
          A mass–spring–dashpot system: a wall on the left is connected to a spring 
          which attaches to a block of mass m; a dashpot is attached on the right side.
        </description>
      </image>
    </figure>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p><strong>1. Model the equation.</strong></p>

    <p>
      No damping → equation is
    </p>
    <me>
      x'' + 4x = f(t).
    </me>

    <p>
      Since the forcing is 1 for <m>0\le t &lt; \pi</m> and 0 afterward,
    </p>

    <me>
      f(t)
      = 1 - u(t-\pi).
    </me>

    <p>
      Initial conditions: <m>x(0)=0</m>, <m>x'(0)=0</m>.
    </p>

    <p><strong>2. Laplace transform.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Transform the ODE:
    </p>

    <me>
      s^{2}X(s) + 4X(s) = \frac{1}{s} - \frac{e^{-\pi s}}{s}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Solve:
    </p>

    <me>
      X(s)
      = \frac{1}{s(s^{2}+4)} - \frac{e^{-\pi s}}{s(s^{2}+4)}.
    </me>

    <p><strong>3. Inverse transform of the unshifted term.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Use the known identity:
    </p>
    <me>
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\!\left[\frac{1}{s(s^{2}+a^{2})}\right]
      = \frac{1}{a^{2}}\bigl(1 - \cos(at)\bigr).
    </me>

    <p>
      Here <m>a=2</m>, so
    </p>
    <me>
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\!\left[\frac{1}{s(s^{2}+4)}\right]
      = \frac{1}{4}\bigl(1 - \cos(2t)\bigr).
    </me>

    <p><strong>4. Inverse transform of the shifted piece.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Use the shifting theorem:
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\!\left[
      e^{-a s} F(s)
      \right]
      = u(t-a)\, f(t-a),
    </me>

    <p>
      where <m>f(t)=\mathcal{L}^{-1}[F(s)]</m>.  
      In our case:
    </p>

    <me>
      F(s)=\frac{1}{s(s^{2}+4)},\qquad
      f(t)=\frac{1}{4}\bigl(1 - \cos(2t)\bigr).
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus:
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\!\left[
      \frac{e^{-\pi s}}{s(s^{2}+4)}
      \right]
      =
      u(t-\pi)\,
      \frac{1}{4}
      \bigl(1 - \cos(2(t-\pi))\bigr).
    </me>

    <p><strong>5. Final solution.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Combining the pieces:
    </p>

    <me>
      x(t)
      =
      \frac14\bigl(1 - \cos(2t)\bigr)
      \;-\;
      u(t-\pi)
      \frac14\bigl(1 - \cos(2(t-\pi))\bigr).
    </me>

    <p>
      Since <m>\cos(2(t-\pi))=\cos(2t)</m>, the expression simplifies nicely:
    </p>

    <me>
      x(t)
      =
      \frac14\bigl(1 - \cos(2t)\bigr)
      -
      u(t-\pi)\frac14\bigl(1 - \cos(2t)\bigr).
    </me>

    <p>
      Factor:
    </p>

    <me>
      x(t)
      =
      \frac14\bigl(1 - \cos(2t)\bigr)\,
      \bigl[1 - u(t-\pi)\bigr].
    </me>

    <p>
      In piecewise form:
    </p>

    <me>
      x(t)
      =
      \begin{cases}
        \frac14\bigl(1 - \cos(2t)\bigr), \amp 0 \le t &lt; \pi,\\[6pt]
        0, \amp t \ge \pi.
      \end{cases}
    </me>

    <p>
      Physically: the system oscillates between 0 and <m>\pi</m>, then returns to equilibrium once the forcing stops.
    </p>

  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-definition-piecewiseC">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use the definition of the Laplace transform to compute (by hand)
      <m>{\cal L}[f(t)]</m> for the function <m>f</m> graphed in 
      <xref ref="GraphLaplaceTransformC"/>.
      Then use technology to verify your result.
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="GraphLaplaceTransformC">
    <caption>Function <m>f(t)</m>.</caption>
    <image width="35%">
      <description>A graph of a function f(t). The function is 0 up to t=1, shown by a horizontal 
        line on the t‑axis ending at a filled dot at t=1. From that point, the graph rises 
        linearly, passing through the point (2,2), and continues upward to the right with an arrow.
      </description>
      <latex-image>
        \begin{tikzpicture}   
   \draw [black!60,line width=0.3pt,-latex] (-1,0) -- (3,0) node [below] at (2.75,0) {$t$};
   \draw [black!60,line width=0.3pt,-latex] (0,-1) -- (0,3) node [left] at (0,2.75) {$f(t)$};
   \draw [linecolor,line width=2pt] (0,0) -- (1,0); 
   \draw [linecolor,line width=2pt,-latex] (1,0) -- (2.5,3); 
   \fill [linecolor] (0,0) circle (3pt);
\fill [linecolor] (2,2) circle (3pt) node [right] at (2.3,2,1) {$(2,2)$};
\foreach \x/\xtext in {1/1, 2/2}
    \draw[shift={(\x,0)}] (0pt,2pt) -- (0pt,-2pt) node[below] {$\xtext$};
\foreach \y/\ytext in {1/1, 2/2}
    \draw[shift={(0,\y)}] (-2pt,0pt) -- (2pt,0pt) node[left] {$\ytext$};
        \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
   </figure>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      From the graph, the function is piecewise-defined:
    </p>

    <me>
      f(t) =
      \begin{cases}
        0 \amp 0 \le t &lt; 1,\\[4pt]
        t-1 \amp t \ge 1.
      \end{cases}
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore the Laplace transform is
    </p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}[f(t)](s)
      = \int_{0}^{1} 0 \cdot e^{-st}\, dt
        + \int_{1}^{\infty} (t-1)e^{-st}\, dt
      = \int_{1}^{\infty} (t-1)e^{-st}\, dt.
    </me>

    <p><strong>Compute the integral.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Substitute <m>u=t-1</m>, hence <m>t=u+1</m> and when <m>t=1</m>, <m>u=0</m>.
      Then
    </p>

    <me>
      \int_{1}^{\infty} (t-1)e^{-st}\, dt
      =
      \int_{0}^{\infty} u\, e^{-s(u+1)}\, du
      =
      e^{-s}
      \int_{0}^{\infty} u\, e^{-su}\, du.
    </me>

    <p>
      Compute the remaining integral:
    </p>

    <me>
      \int_{0}^{\infty} u\, e^{-su}\, du
      = \frac{1}{s^{2}}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Hence
    </p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}[f(t)](s)
      = e^{-s}\, \frac{1}{s^{2}}
      = \frac{e^{-s}}{s^{2}}.
    </me>

  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="laplace-inverse-partialfractions-big">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Use partial fractions to evaluate
    </p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}^{-1}\!\left\{
        \frac{s^{2} + 6s + 9}{(s-1)(s-2)(s+4)}
      \right\}
    </me>

    <p>
      by hand.  Use technology to verify the result.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p><strong>1. Set up partial fractions.</strong></p>

    <p>
      We want to write
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{s^{2}+6s+9}{(s-1)(s-2)(s+4)}
      =
      \frac{A}{s-1} + \frac{B}{s-2} + \frac{C}{s+4}.
    </me>

    <p>Multiply through:</p>

    <me>
      s^{2}+6s+9
      =
      A(s-2)(s+4)
      + B(s-1)(s+4)
      + C(s-1)(s-2).
    </me>

    <p><strong>2. Evaluate at convenient values.</strong></p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>s=1</m>:
        </p>
        <me>
          1+6+9 = A(1-2)(1+4)
          \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
          16 = -5A \quad\Longrightarrow\quad A = -\frac{16}{5}.
        </me>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <m>s=2</m>:
        </p>
        <me>
          4 + 12 + 9 = B(2-1)(2+4)
          \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
          25 = 6B
          \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
          B = \frac{25}{6}.
        </me>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          <m>s=-4</m>:
        </p>
        <me>
          16 - 24 + 9 = C(-4-1)(-4-2)
          \\[4pt]
          1 = C( -5)( -6 )
          \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
          C = \frac{1}{30}.
        </me>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>3. Write the decomposition.</strong></p>

    <me>
      \frac{s^{2}+6s+9}{(s-1)(s-2)(s+4)}
      =
      -\frac{16}{5}\frac{1}{s-1}
      + \frac{25}{6}\frac{1}{s-2}
      + \frac{1}{30}\frac{1}{s+4}.
    </me>

    <p><strong>4. Inverse Laplace transform term‑by‑term.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Use <m>{\cal L}^{-1}\{1/(s-a)\} = e^{at}</m>.  
      Thus:
    </p>

    <me>
      y(t)
      =
      -\frac{16}{5} e^{t}
      + \frac{25}{6} e^{2t}
      + \frac{1}{30} e^{-4t}.
    </me>

  </solution>
</exercise>

<!-- <exercise xml:id="laplace-ivp-e-4t">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Keeping the result of the previous problem in mind, solve (by hand) the IVP
    </p>

    <me>
      y'' - 3y' + 2y = e^{-4t}, 
      \qquad 
      y(0)=1,\; y'(0)=5
    </me>

    <p>
      using the Laplace transform.  
      Verify the result using appropriate technology.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p><strong>1. Take Laplace transforms.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Use the formulas:
    </p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}[y''] = s^{2}Y - s\,y(0) - y'(0),
      \quad
      {\cal L}[y'] = sY - y(0).
    </me>

    <p>
      Substitute <m>y(0)=1</m>, <m>y'(0)=5</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      s^{2}Y - s - 5 
      \;-\; 3(sY - 1)
      \;+\; 2Y
      \;=\;
      \frac{1}{s+4}.
    </me>

    <p><strong>2. Simplify the left side.</strong></p>

    <me>
      s^{2}Y - s - 5 - 3sY + 3 + 2Y
      =
      (s^{2} - 3s + 2)Y \;-\; s \;-\; 2.
    </me>

    <p>
      But 
      <m>s^{2}-3s+2 = (s-1)(s-2)</m>,  
      so the equation becomes:
    </p>

    <me>
      (s^{2}-3s+2)Y - s - 2 = \frac{1}{s+4}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Solve for <m>Y(s)</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      Y(s)
      =
      \frac{1}{(s+4)(s-1)(s-2)}
      +
      \frac{s+2}{(s-1)(s-2)}.
    </me>

    <p><strong>3. Split into two pieces.</strong></p>

    <p>
      First write:
    </p>

    <me>
      Y(s)
      =
      \underbrace{\frac{1}{(s+4)(s-1)(s-2)}}_{\text{forced term}}
      \;+\;
      \underbrace{\frac{s+2}{(s-1)(s-2)}}_{\text{homogeneous term}}.
    </me>

    <p><strong>4. Invert the homogeneous part.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Decompose:
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{s+2}{(s-1)(s-2)}
      =
      \frac{-3}{s-1}
      +
      \frac{4}{s-2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus
    </p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}^{-1}\!\left[\frac{s+2}{(s-1)(s-2)}\right]
      =
      -3 e^{t} + 4 e^{2t}.
    </me>

    <p><strong>5. Invert the forced part using the Shift Theorem.</strong></p>

    <p>
      We want 
      <m>
      {\cal L}^{-1}\!\left[\dfrac{1}{(s+4)(s-1)(s-2)}\right].
      </m>
    </p>

    <p>
      Factor out the shift:
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{1}{(s+4)(s-1)(s-2)}
      =
      \frac{1}{s+4}
      \cdot
      \frac{1}{(s-1)(s-2)}
      =
      e^{-4t}
      * 
      {\cal L}^{-1}\!\left[\frac{1}{(s-1)(s-2)}\right].
    </me>

    <p>
      Compute the simpler inverse:
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{1}{(s-1)(s-2)}
      =
      \frac{-1}{s-1} + \frac{1}{s-2}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Hence
    </p>

    <me>
      g(t)
      =
      -e^{t} + e^{2t}.
    </me>

    <p>
      By the shifting theorem:
    </p>

    <me>
      {\cal L}^{-1}\!\left[\frac{1}{(s+4)(s-1)(s-2)}\right]
      =
      e^{-4(t-0)}\,g(t)
      =
      e^{-4t}\bigl(-e^{t} + e^{2t}\bigr).
    </me>

    <p><strong>6. Combine both parts.</strong></p>

    <me>
      y(t)
      =
      (-3e^{t} + 4e^{2t})
      \;+\;
      e^{-4t}\bigl(-e^{t} + e^{2t}\bigr).
    </me>

    <p>
      That is the final closed‑form solution.
    </p>

  </solution>
</exercise> -->

<exercise xml:id="laplace-ivp-piecewise-force-again">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Solve the IVP
    </p>

    <me>
      y'' + 2y' + y = f(t), 
      \qquad 
      y(0)=0,\; y'(0)=0,
    </me>

    <p>
      where
    </p>

    <me>
      f(t) =
      \left\{
      \begin{array}{cr}
        0 \amp 0 \le t &lt; 1 \\[4pt]
        1 \amp 1 \le t &lt; 2 \\[4pt]
       -1 \amp 2 \le t &lt; 3 \\[4pt]
        0 \amp 3 \le t &lt; \infty
      \end{array}
      \right\}.
    </me>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p><strong>1. Rewrite the forcing using step functions.</strong></p>

    <p>
      The piecewise function becomes:
    </p>

    <me>
      f(t) = u(t-1) - 2u(t-2) + u(t-3).
    </me>

    <p>
      (Check:  
      On <m>[1,2)</m> it equals <m>1</m>;  
      on <m>[2,3)</m> it equals <m>-1</m>;  
      for <m>t\ge 3</m> it returns to <m>0</m>.)
    </p>

    <p><strong>2. Apply the Laplace transform.</strong></p>

    <p>
      With <m>y(0)=0</m>, <m>y'(0)=0</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}\{y''\} = s^{2}Y(s),\qquad
      \mathcal{L}\{2y'\} = 2sY(s),\qquad
      \mathcal{L}\{y\} = Y(s).
    </me>

    <p>
      So the ODE becomes:
    </p>

    <me>
      (s^{2} + 2s + 1) Y(s)
      = \frac{e^{-s}}{s} - \frac{2e^{-2s}}{s} + \frac{e^{-3s}}{s}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Since <m>s^{2} + 2s + 1 = (s+1)^{2}</m>, we have:
    </p>

    <me>
      Y(s)
      =
      \frac{e^{-s}}{s(s+1)^{2}}
      - \frac{2e^{-2s}}{s(s+1)^{2}}
      + \frac{e^{-3s}}{s(s+1)^{2}}.
    </me>

    <p><strong>3. Invert the non‑shifted kernel.</strong></p>

    <p>
      First compute
    </p>

    <me>
      h(t) = \mathcal{L}^{-1}\!\left[\frac{1}{s(s+1)^{2}}\right].
    </me>

    <p>
      Do partial fractions:
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{1}{s(s+1)^{2}}
      =
      \frac{1}{s}
      - \frac{1}{s+1}
      - \frac{1}{(s+1)^{2}}.
    </me>

    <p>Thus:</p>

    <me>
      h(t)
      =
      1 - e^{-t} - t e^{-t}.
    </me>

    <p><strong>4. Apply the shifting theorem.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Using
    </p>

    <me>
      \mathcal{L}^{-1}\!\left[\frac{e^{-as}}{s(s+1)^{2}}\right]
      = u(t-a)\,h(t-a),
    </me>

    <p>
      the solution becomes:
    </p>

    <me>
      y(t)
      = u(t-1)h(t-1)
      - 2u(t-2)h(t-2)
      + u(t-3)h(t-3),
    </me>

    <p>
      with <m>h(t) = 1 - e^{-t} - t e^{-t}</m>.
    </p>

    <p><strong>5. Final explicit form.</strong></p>

    <md>
      <mrow> y(t)
      \amp =
      u(t-1)\!\left[\,1 - e^{-(t-1)} - (t-1)e^{-(t-1)}\right] </mrow>
      
      <mrow> \ \ \amp - 2u(t-2)\!\left[\,1 - e^{-(t-2)} - (t-2)e^{-(t-2)}\right] </mrow>
      
      <mrow> \ \ \amp + u(t-3)\!\left[\,1 - e^{-(t-3)} - (t-3)e^{-(t-3)}\right]. </mrow>
    </md>

  </solution>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>

      <section xml:id="sec-Advancedlearningobjectives32">
        <title>Advanced learning objectives</title>

        <p>
          In addition to mastering the basic objectives, here are the tasks you should be able 
          to perform, with practice:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
     Apply the full set of derivative-transform formulas to solve higher‑order linear ODEs with given initial conditions.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Use algebraic manipulation in the <m>s</m>-domain—including partial fractions—to prepare 
      expressions for inverse Laplace transforms.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Interpret the Laplace‑domain solution in terms of the structure of the original differential 
      equation, including forced responses and natural modes.
            </p>
          </li>

        </ul>

      </section>


</handout>